This model pattern is based upon the philosophy that a system is composed of a product plus a process.
there are two levels the system where we rationalize about the process in which any product will be use and we arrive at highlevel funtions the product must fufli
and the product level where we specify how the prodcut will fufil those functions.
This sets up the use case hierarchy where we can basically assume that there are two levels when we talk aboht a system. the system black box where we assume that the system as a whole completes the goals of the stakeholders. and the system white box level. system white box we will specify which part of the system is performing the various goals as either the process or the product. this sets up the product level where we get into specifying what the product must do and the allocation of functions to the system architecture.

The Actors Catalogue was created to promote reuse of standard behavioral elements that describe common stakeholders, actors, End Users, and Personas within the digital ecosystem. This catalogue is meant to be the repository where these elements are compiled and shared throughout the various model packages. CATALOGUE INTENDED USE Solutions should be developed in collaboration with a few influential decision makers and ensuring “end users” who seek to use the results. However, IA projects typically engage a larger group of potential end users during the implementation phase than collaborative research projects. This includes stakeholders that may have unique or competing views on the topic. This tool will guide you through a two-step process of identifying potential end users and stakeholder participants, and developing an appropriate role for each in the project. You will likely find it helpful to revisit this process periodically, as the project evolves and you gain a better understanding of your end users, stakeholders and their needs. Each product model should share some version of this catalogue. For projects this catalogue should be for the starting point for the stakeholder analysis completed as part of the mission analysis. Applicable stakeholders should be copied out of the catalogue and evaluated for project applicability. Any needed changes should be evaluated with that stakeholder and an architecture review board. Actors can be people, other systems, time triggers, or event triggers. An actor specifies a role played by a user or any other system that interacts with the subject. It may represent roles played by human users, external hardware, or other subjects. Actors are always outside the system and interact directly with it by initiating a use case, provide input to it, and/or receive outputs from it. While a single physical instance may play the role of several different actors, an actor does not necessarily represent specific physical entities, i.e. a timer that triggers sending of an e-mail reminder. UML:TaggedValue.value:
The use case Hierarchy follow the basic recursive pattern that is found in several references. Most notable "Writing Effective Use Cases" by Alister Cockburn. This pattern is based upon highlevel goals that are captures as a use case oval on the use case diagram, but the contents are higher level than the use case. Goals focus on the description, the value, and what the user expects.
THe Use cases are more detailed and provide the flow, list alt flows, triggers, pre/post conditions, etc. Use cases are generic flows that the actor expects from the use case.
Scenarios are very detailed instances of use cases. These have specific values for the pre/post conditions and provide concerete examples of the use case basic and alt flow.

A Use Case diagram is used to describe the goals of the system such as those associated with the mission objectives. The Missions are documented as an extension of the use case modeling method. Each of the main mission objectives may be decomposed into more specific Missions, but don't always have to. The Missions Package in addition to the Missions can also contain example use cases that exemplify specific instances of the generic Mission being fulfilled.

UML:UseCase.name: Use Case- Land Plane and Taxi to Gate

UML:TaggedValue.value:
DESCRIPTION The airplane lands and travels to the gate where all the passengers get off. PRECONDITION
  1. The plane is in the air
  2. The airplane is approaching the airport
  3. The passengers are seated with seatbelts on
  4. The flight attendants have prepared the cabin for landing
TRIGGER Airport Air traffic Control clears the plane for landing ASSUMPTIONS
  1. There is a gate ready
POSTCONDITION
  1. Plane is at a gate
  2. Plane is on the ground
  3. All passengers are off the plane
  4. All passengers are in the airport terminal
  5. All luggage is unloaded
BASIC FLOW
  1. Plane is cleared for landing
  2. Plane approaches runway
  3. Plane lands
  4. Plane taxis directly to the gate
  5. Plane parks at gate
  6. Plight attendants open the doors
  7. Passengers deplane
ALTERNATE FLOW
  1. Plane Taxis for a long time
  2. Plane parks on taxi way
  3. Plane waits for gate to be open]
  4. Plane taxis to Bus station

Scenarios are specific instances of use cases with detailed steps, conditions and values that provide concrete examples of the generic flow paths described in use cases. Scenarios should be completed with sufficient level of detail that the user experience can be expressed or that the white box actor's behaviors can be quantified. The following is a best practice template in how to describe a scenario: DESCRIPTION Provide a clear and concise description of what the scenario entails. Hint at the key preconditions/or post conditions that make this scenario unique and important to the system. DIFFERENTIATOR Provide a one liner as to why this scenario is different from the generic use case and/or other scenarios. UNIQUE OUTCOME Describe what unique outcome is realized through this scenario that makes it important to the system designers. TRIGGER Describe the trigger that kicks off the scenario. This is the first step in it being unique. STAKEHOLDER INTENT Describe the stakeholders intent in a one liner. Note the stakeholder could be a system actor dependent upon the level of the use case. PRECONDITIONS One key thing that makes a scenario different from a use case is the quantifying of specific values. Provide the preconditions with specific values, states, locations, etc. POSTCONDITIONS Provide a bullet pointed list of the specific post conditions. Provide values that can be measured or easily observed. ASSUMPTIONS List the assumptions that this scenario is based upon. In many instances some of the main differences between scenarios will be assumptions in preconditions that initiate the event or post conditions when the event is over. BASIC SCENARIO FLOW Provide the basic flow of the scenario step by step in a number list.

VALUE Describe the value the stakeholder/user is expecting to get out of the system from this use case. MISSION DESCRIPTION A basic description of the mission to be accomplished. BACKGROUND Any background information needed to provide context for the mission. INCLUDES The scope included in the mission. It is important to specifically call out what the mission includes. This is used to set up guardrails for scope of problem that the design team will solve. Unclear scope will almost certainty lead to gold plating features and churn in solution brainstorming later in the project. ASSUMPTIONS The assumptions on the mission including environmental, application, types of supported mission workflows, things that the mission is not including should be listed here. ALL things in science and engineering are based upon assumptions stated which should be clearly stated.
